FBIS4-15211 "drsov067_a_94023" FBIS-SOV-94-067 Daily Report 7 Apr 1994 RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS Tension Between Crimean, Ukrainian Authorities Viewed Tension Between Crimean, Ukrainian Authorities Viewed LD0704131194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel Network in Russian 1100 GMT 7 Apr 94 LD0704131194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel Network Russian BFN [From the "Novosti" newscast] [Text] It appears that the battle between the authorities of Ukraine and Crimea has worsened. Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov says the situation that has taken shape on the peninsula is due to provocations by the powers that be in Ukraine. [Correspondent Vladimir Plotnikov] Kravchuk's decree appointing a representative of the Ukrainian president in Crimea has aroused particular opposition. The leadership of Crimea's republican movement, Russian Society, [Russkoye Obshchestvo] today called on citizens to rally in support of the Crimean president. [Begin Crimean President Meshkov recording] [Words indistinct] that Ukraine's current leadership is the most dangerous, from the point of view of maintaining peace and calm in Europe. This leadership has relied on, and unfortunately continues to rely on, extreme nationalist forces in Ukraine and can only act within a framework designed by the nationalists. [end recording] [Plotnikov] It may be by chance, but the war of decrees broke out on the eve of the second round of elections to the Ukrainian and Crimean parliaments. It might be expected that this war will help consolidate Meshkov's supporters. Even the autonomous republic's Supreme Soviet, with its current composition and history of total subservience to Kiev, has spoken against the appointment of a representative for Kravchuk in Crimea. [Video shows Meshkov talking to journalists and a rally in Crimea]
